MultipleChoice.question:
The net change in F over [0, 3] can be visualized as the signed area under F^\prime(x) = 1 - 2x from x = 0 to x =3\text{.}
Signed area under 1 - 2x
Based on the signed area in the figure, the net change is expected to be \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}\text{.}

ShortAnswer.question:
The net change in F over [0, 3] is
F(3) - F(0) = \displaystyle \int_0^3 (1 - 2x) \, dx = (x - x^2) {\Large|}_0^3
Completing the integration gives \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}}\text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
Completing the integration gives the net change in F over [0, 3]\text{:}
\begin{align*}F(3) - F(0) & = \displaystyle \int_0^3 (1 - 2x) \, dx \\& = (x - x^2) {\Large|}_0^3 \\& = (3 - 3^2) - (0 - 0^2) \\& = 3 - 9 \\& = -6\end{align*}
Note that the net change is a loss, which matches what was expected based on the signed area.

MultipleChoice.question:
The carâ€™s velocity at time t (in hours) is
v(t) = \begin{cases} \, \, \, \, 60 \qquad 0 \leq t <2 \quad \\ -40 \qquad 2 < t \leq 5 \quad \end{cases}
The carâ€™s displacement at the end of the 5\text{-hour} drive can be found using \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.question:
The carâ€™s displacement at the end of the 5\text{-hour} drive is
\displaystyle \int_0^2 60 \, dt + \displaystyle \int_2^5 (-40) \, dt = 60t {\Large|}_0^2 + (-40t) {\Large|}_2^5
So the displacement is \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
The carâ€™s displacement is
\begin{align*} \displaystyle \int_0^2 60 \, dt + \displaystyle \int_2^5 (-40) \, dt & = 60t {\Large|}_0^2 + (-40t) {\Large|}_2^5 \\& = \left(60(2) - 60(0) \right) + \left( -40(5) - (-40)(2) \right) \\& = (120 - 0) + (-200 + 80) \\& = 0 \text{ miles}\end{align*}
Velocity is 60 from t = 0 to t = 2 and -40 from t = 2 to t = 5. Area under velocity is +120 from t = 0 to t = 2 and -120 from t = 2 to t = 5.

An antiderivative of 2t is t^2 by the constant multiple and power rules. An antiderivative of -6 is -6t by the constant rule.
Using these antiderivatives and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, the definite integral is
\displaystyle \int_0^{4} (2t-6) \, dt = (t^2 - 6t) {\Large|}_0^{4}

ShortAnswer.question:
The carâ€™s displacement over [0, 4] is
\displaystyle \int_0^{4} (2t - 6) \, dt = (t^2 - 6t) {\Large|}_0^{4}
Completing the integration gives the net change as \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
Completing the integration gives the displacement over [0, 4] \text{:}
\begin{align*} \displaystyle \int_0^{4} (2t - 6) \, dt & = (t^2 - 6t) {\Large|}_0^{4} \\& = \left( 4^2 - 6(4) \right) - \left(0^2 - 6(0) \right) \\& =(16 - 24) - (0 - 0) \\ & = -8\end{align*}
So the particleâ€™s displacement is -8\text{ meters.} If movement to the right corresponds to a positive velocity, and movement to the left corresponds to a negative velocity, then the particle ends 8\text{ meters} to the left of where the particle starts.
The negative value makes sense when considering the graph of v(t). Note that the area below the t-axis is larger than the area above the t-axis.
Signed area under v(t) = 2t - 6 from t = 0 to t=4

