MultipleChoice.question:
The carâ€™s velocity at time t (in hours) is
v(t) = \begin{cases} \, \, \, \, 60 \qquad 0 \leq t <2 \quad \\ -40 \qquad 2 < t \leq 5 \quad \end{cases}
The carâ€™s total distance traveled at the end of the 5\text{-hour} drive can be found using \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.question:
The carâ€™s total distance traveled at the end of the 5\text{-hour} drive is
\displaystyle \int_0^2 60 \, dt + \displaystyle \int_2^5 40 \, dt = 60t {\Large|}_0^2 + 40t {\Large|}_2^5
So the total distance is \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
The carâ€™s total distance traveled is
\begin{align*} \displaystyle \int_0^2 60 \, dt + \displaystyle \int_2^5 40 \, dt & = 60t {\Large|}_0^2 + 40t {\Large|}_2^5 \\& = \left(60(2) - 60(0) \right) + \left( 40(5) - (40)(2) \right) \\& = (120 - 0) + (200 - 80) \\& = 240 \text{ miles}\end{align*}
Speed is 60 from t = 0 to t = 2 and 40 from t = 2 to t = 5. Area under speed is 120 from t = 0 to t = 2 and 120 from t = 2 to t = 5.

The velocity can change signs at values of t where v(t) = 0 \text{.}
Setting v(t) = 0 gives
\begin{align*}64 - 32t & = 0 \\ 64 & = 32t && \text{Add} \\ \frac{64}{32} & = t && \text{Divide} \\ 2 & = t && \text{Simplify}\end{align*}
So the velocity is equal to 0 at t = 2. Checking the sign of the velocity on either side of t = 2 reveals that the velocity is positive before t = 2 and negative after t = 2. So the velocity does change signs at t =2 \text{.}

