TextResource.Text:
A small online business sells custom printed T-shirts. The business runs a market research study and finds that the marginal revenue from selling x\text{ shirts per week} is
R^\prime(x) = 9 + 2x
Find the net change in revenue if sales increase from 5\text{ shirts per week} to 10\text{ shirts per week}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
An antiderivative of 9 is 9x by the constant rule. An antiderivative of 2x is x^2 by the power rule.
Using these antiderivatives and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, the definite integral is
\displaystyle \int_5^{10} (9+2x) \, dx = (9x + x^2){\Large|}_5^{10}

ShortAnswer.question:
The net change in R over [5, 10] is
\displaystyle \int_5^{10} (9+2x) \, dx = (9x + x^2){\Large|}_5^{10}
Completing the integration gives the net change as \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
Completing the integration gives the net change in R over [5, 10] \text{:}
\begin{align*} \displaystyle \int_5^{10} (9+2x) \, dx & = (9x+x^2) {\Large|}_5^{10} \\& = \left( 9(10) + (10)^2 \right) - \left( 9(5) + 5^2 \right)\\& = 190 - 70 \\ & = 120\end{align*}
So the net change in the revenue if sales increase from 5 to 10\text{ shirts per week} is \$120 \text{.} If this increase in revenue is larger than the corresponding increase in cost, the business will know that it is profitable to increase sales to 10\text{ shirts per week.}

TextResource.Text:
Salmonella bacteria multiply very quickly under the right conditions, so that the growth rate of the bacteria initially resembles exponential growth.
Ex: A population P(t) of salmonella bacteria is growing at a rate of P^\prime(t) = 2e^t\text{ thousand bacteria per hour.} Find the net change in population size over the first 4\text{ hours.}
Initial growth rate P'(t) = 2e^t of a population of salmonella bacteria

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
An antiderivative of 2e^t is 2e^t by the constant and exponential rules.
Using this antiderivative and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, the definite integral is
\displaystyle \int_0^{4} 2e^t \, dt = 2e^t {\Large|}_0^{4}

ShortAnswer.question:
The net change in P over [0, 4] is
\displaystyle \int_0^{4} 2e^t \, dt = 2e^t{\Large|}_0^{4}
Completing the integration gives the net change as \underline{\phantom{XXXXXX}} \text{.}

ShortAnswer.CorrectExplanation:
Completing the integration gives the net change in P over [0, 4] \text{:}
\begin{align*} \displaystyle \int_0^{4} 2e^t \, dt & = 2e^t {\Large|}_0^{4} \\& = 2e^4 - 2e^0 \\& = 2e^4 - 2\end{align*}
So the net change in the salmonella bacteria population over the first 4\text{ hours} is 2e^4 - 2 \approx 107\text{ thousand bacteria.} This rapid bacterial growth is what makes salmonella bacteria so dangerous.

